# ============================================================================
# 1. Header / Safety
# ============================================================================
#
# Copy this file to .env and adjust locally:
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#
# - Never commit the real .env (it is already git-ignored).
# - Never commit anything under volumes/ (uploads, document-data, ocr-models,
#   benchmark/ — all git-ignored via /volumes/*).
# - Local documents, extracted text, OCR output, PII results, and benchmark
#   reports may contain real personal data. Treat everything under volumes/
#   as sensitive, even in local development.
# - Most changes below only take effect after a container recreate, not a
#   simple restart: `make up` / `make up-pii` / `make up-ocr` / `make up-full`
#   again (they always rebuild+recreate). Changing PII_* also means existing
#   pii_result artifacts on disk still reflect the *old* configuration until
#   you re-run PII detection for a document (POST /api/documents/{id}/pii).

# ============================================================================
# 2. Quick Start — Recommended Defaults
# ============================================================================
#
# Recommended local full-engine setup for this project:
#   - OCR enabled   -> make up-ocr / make up-full  (needs `make ocr-models` once)
#   - PII enabled   -> make up-pii / make up-full
#   - PII_PROFILE=insurance-at-de   (see section 10 for why, not structured-only)
#   - PII_CANDIDATE_VALIDATION_ENABLED=true
#
# This file sets exactly that as the PII default further down. The build
# profile itself (OCR/PII installed or not) is normally chosen by the make
# target you run, not by this file — see section 7.

# ============================================================================
# 3. Web / Ports
# ============================================================================

# Host port for the web app (nginx frontend). Open http://localhost:${WEB_PORT}
WEB_PORT=8080

# ============================================================================
# 4. Upload Limits
# ============================================================================
# Local development only. Increase MAX_UPLOAD_BYTES for larger PDFs if needed.
# Only add extensions the engine can actually process — an allowed extension
# with no matching Audit/OCR support will fail later in the pipeline, not at
# upload time.

# Maximum accepted upload size in bytes (default 10 MiB).
MAX_UPLOAD_BYTES=10485760

# Comma-separated allowed file extensions (lowercase, no dot).
ALLOWED_EXTENSIONS=pdf,docx,png,jpg,jpeg

# ============================================================================
# 5. Storage Paths
# ============================================================================
# Originals and application-managed data are deliberately kept in two
# separate roots so a bug in one cannot silently mix into the other. The app
# refuses to start if the two resolve to the same or a nested directory.
#
# Compose mounts these container paths from the host directories
# ./volumes/uploads and ./volumes/document-data respectively. Do not point
# both at the same host path, and do not commit anything under volumes/.

UPLOAD_STORAGE_DIR=/data/uploads
DOCUMENT_DATA_DIR=/data/document-data

# ============================================================================
# 6. Logging
# ============================================================================
# Log level: DEBUG | INFO | WARNING | ERROR | CRITICAL
# Use DEBUG only locally and briefly — it is more verbose, not less safe by
# itself, but pair it with care: the app never logs PII/full document text by
# design (Presidio/spaCy/OCR library logs are also kept away from raw
# content), and DEBUG should not become a habit that encourages logging
# candidate values while troubleshooting.
LOG_LEVEL=INFO

# ============================================================================
# 7. Runtime Build Profiles
# ============================================================================
# Normally you do not set these here. Use the make targets, which set the
# matching build args for you:
#
#   make up          -> INSTALL_OCR=false INSTALL_PII=false  (slim, default)
#   make up-pii       -> INSTALL_OCR=false INSTALL_PII=true
#   make up-ocr       -> INSTALL_OCR=true  INSTALL_PII=false  (needs `make ocr-models` first)
#   make up-full      -> INSTALL_OCR=true  INSTALL_PII=true   (needs `make ocr-models` first)
#
# The values below only matter if you run `docker compose` directly instead
# of a make target.

# Build the backend with the optional PaddleOCR/PaddlePaddle runtime.
# INSTALL_OCR=false is enough for upload, audit, DOCX extraction, and PDF
# text-layer extraction — only image documents and scanned PDF pages need OCR.
INSTALL_OCR=true

# Build Presidio, spaCy, and the pinned German spaCy model into the backend
# image. INSTALL_PII=false disables the PII runtime entirely (the /pii
# endpoint then returns 503).
INSTALL_PII=true

# ============================================================================
# 8. OCR Runtime
# ============================================================================
# Ignored when INSTALL_OCR=false.
#
# - Models must be provisioned once with `make ocr-models` (downloads into
#   ./volumes/ocr-models). There is no runtime download: a missing model
#   directory returns 503 instead of silently fetching one.
# - The Latin recognizer below covers German/Latin-script text, including
#   umlauts and ß — the default (Chinese/English) recognizer does not.
# - OCR is synchronous and can be slow on CPU for multi-page scans (the
#   nginx proxy timeout is raised to 600s to accommodate this).
# - Use `make up-ocr` (OCR only) or `make up-full` (OCR + PII) to run it.

# Container-internal model root, mounted read-only from ./volumes/ocr-models.
OCR_MODEL_DIR=/models/ocr
# Names of the provisioned models; must match what fetch-ocr-models.sh
# downloaded. Empty = let PaddleOCR pick its own default name.
OCR_DETECTION_MODEL_NAME=PP-OCRv5_mobile_det
OCR_RECOGNITION_MODEL_NAME=latin_PP-OCRv5_mobile_rec

# ============================================================================
# 9. PII Runtime
# ============================================================================
# PII Workstation v1 uses one configured language/model and performs
# detection only — it never anonymizes, masks, or alters the source text.
#
# If, after changing anything in this section, PII detection on a document
# looks unexpectedly empty, see the "If PII detects nothing" checklist in
# section 14 before assuming something is broken.

PII_LANGUAGE=de
PII_SPACY_MODEL=de_core_news_sm

# Minimum detection score kept in the final result. 0.5 is the shipped
# default. Candidate validation (section 11) can cap a candidate's score at
# 0.3 — below this threshold — which is how it excludes an obvious false
# positive from the final result without a separate on/off flag per type.
PII_SCORE_THRESHOLD=0.5

# Named coverage profile — see section 10 for what each one detects.
# Recommended for this project: insurance-at-de (set below).
#
# Design note: the *application code* falls back to the conservative
# "structured-only" profile if PII_PROFILE is left completely unset (see
# backend/app/config.py and docker-compose.yml). This .env.example instead
# recommends "insurance-at-de" as the practical local default for this
# project, because structured-only alone under-detects for insurance/legal
# documents. If you delete this file's PII_PROFILE line entirely (rather
# than commenting it out), you fall back to the conservative code default,
# not to this recommendation.
PII_PROFILE=insurance-at-de

# Engine-5 candidate validation: subtractive post-processing over already
# detected candidates (see section 11). Recommended: true.
PII_CANDIDATE_VALIDATION_ENABLED=true

# ============================================================================
# 10. PII Profiles Explained
# ============================================================================
#
# structured-only:
#   High precision, low coverage. Detects only basic structured types:
#   EMAIL_ADDRESS, PHONE_NUMBER, IBAN_CODE, CREDIT_CARD, IP_ADDRESS, URL.
#   Good for a minimal, privacy-strict smoke test. Too narrow as the
#   day-to-day default for insurance/legal documents — this is the
#   conservative code fallback, not the recommended local profile.
#
# insurance-at-de:
#   Recommended default for this project (set above).
#   structured-only + AT/DE and insurance/legal/business identifiers:
#   UID_AT, FN_AT, SVNR_AT, TAX_ID_AT, BIC, LICENSE_PLATE_AT,
#   PASSPORT_NUMBER, ID_CARD_NUMBER, POLICY_NUMBER, CLAIM_NUMBER,
#   CONTRACT_NUMBER, CASE_NUMBER, FILE_REFERENCE, REPORT_NUMBER,
#   ASSESSMENT_NUMBER, INVOICE_NUMBER, OFFER_NUMBER, CUSTOMER_NUMBER,
#   PROJECT_ID, TRANSACTION_ID, USER_ID.
#   Does NOT enable broad PERSON/ORGANIZATION/LOCATION NER.
#
# broad-review:
#   insurance-at-de + PERSON, ORGANIZATION, LOCATION.
#   More coverage, more false positives. Intended for a human-reviewed
#   workflow, not as an unattended default.
#
# review-heavy:
#   broad-review + DATE_TIME. Maximum review mode: nothing is meant to be
#   missed, at the cost of the highest candidate volume and the most noise.
#   Good as a debugging/comparison profile, not as the default.
#
# PERSON/ORGANIZATION/LOCATION stay opt-in through broad-review/review-heavy
# because the small German spaCy model tags them at a near-fixed confidence
# score that PII_SCORE_THRESHOLD alone cannot filter (candidate validation,
# section 11, is what makes those two profiles usable at all). DATE_TIME is
# opt-in only in review-heavy for the same reason.

# ============================================================================
# 11. Candidate Validation (Engine-5)
# ============================================================================
#
# Candidate validation is subtractive post-processing over candidates that
# Presidio/spaCy already detected. It never detects new entities and never
# replaces a recognizer. For each already-detected candidate it decides:
#   - KEEP        — unchanged
#   - SCORE_DOWN  — score capped at 0.3 (see PII_SCORE_THRESHOLD above);
#                   this is how an obvious false positive falls out of the
#                   final result without a separate per-type toggle
#   - DROP        — removed outright (e.g. a bare function word tagged as
#                   PERSON)
#
# true  = remove/downscore obvious false positives (recommended)
# false = raw Presidio/recognizer output, nothing filtered
#
# Debugging: you can temporarily set this to false to compare raw detection
# against the validated result. After changing it, recreate the container
# and re-run PII detection for the document you are comparing — an existing
# pii_result artifact still reflects whatever setting produced it. Do not
# leave it disabled long-term outside of that comparison; on the review-heavy
# NER types (PERSON/ORGANIZATION/LOCATION/DATE_TIME) it is what keeps false
# positives manageable.
# (Already set to true in section 9 above; this section only explains it.)

# ============================================================================
# 12. Advanced: Manual Entity Override (PII_ENTITY_TYPES)
# ============================================================================
#
# Do not set PII_ENTITY_TYPES unless you intentionally want a custom
# allowlist instead of a named profile.
#
# - Unset or commented out (the normal case): PII_PROFILE (section 9)
#   controls which entity types are detected.
# - Set to a non-empty comma-separated list: this list *overrides*
#   PII_PROFILE entirely — the profile is then reported as "custom" in
#   pii_result, and PII_PROFILE itself is ignored for entity selection.
# - Set to an explicitly empty value (PII_ENTITY_TYPES=): treated the same
#   as unset/commented out — it falls back to PII_PROFILE, it does NOT mean
#   "detect nothing." An empty override was kept backwards-compatible on
#   purpose so an unset-but-present variable (e.g. from an older .env or a
#   Compose default) cannot accidentally disable detection entirely.
#
# PII_PROFILE and PII_ENTITY_TYPES are not two equal ways to configure the
# same thing: PII_PROFILE is the normal control, PII_ENTITY_TYPES is an
# escape hatch that overrides it. Keep this commented out unless you are
# doing a targeted debug/test run with a specific type list.
#
# Example (commented out):
# PII_ENTITY_TYPES=EMAIL_ADDRESS,PHONE_NUMBER,IBAN_CODE,CREDIT_CARD,IP_ADDRESS,URL,UID_AT,FN_AT,BIC

# ============================================================================
# 13. Memory / Performance
# ============================================================================
# Optional container memory limit. The ocr/pii/full make targets raise this
# automatically for the heavier runtimes (OCR and spaCy/Presidio both need
# more RAM than the slim baseline). If the backend gets OOM-killed or you see
# 503s under load, raise this value. OCR on CPU can also simply be slow
# rather than out of memory — check `make logs` to tell the two apart.
BACKEND_MEMORY_LIMIT=512M

# ============================================================================
# 14. Troubleshooting Notes
# ============================================================================
#
# If PII detects nothing:
#   1. Check INSTALL_PII=true and that you started with `make up-pii` or
#      `make up-full` (not plain `make up`, which is PII-disabled by design).
#   2. Check PII_PROFILE. structured-only is narrow by design — try
#      insurance-at-de (recommended) or review-heavy for a wider comparison.
#   3. Make sure PII_ENTITY_TYPES (section 12) is commented out unless you
#      intentionally set a custom allowlist — a stray non-empty value there
#      silently overrides PII_PROFILE.
#   4. Recreate the containers after any .env change
#      (`make up-pii` / `make up-full` again; they rebuild+recreate).
#   5. Re-run PII detection for the document (POST .../pii) — an existing
#      pii_result artifact may be from an older profile or configuration and
#      is never mutated in place.
#   6. For a raw-vs-validated comparison, temporarily set
#      PII_CANDIDATE_VALIDATION_ENABLED=false, recreate, and re-run.
#   7. Check the API response itself (GET .../pii), not only the UI — the UI
#      only overlays highlights when its input text artifact still matches
#      the current OCR/Text result; the entity list is unaffected by that.
#
# If OCR returns 503:
#   1. Run `make ocr-models` (idempotent; downloads into ./volumes/ocr-models).
#   2. Use `make up-ocr` or `make up-full` (not plain `make up`).
#   3. Check OCR_MODEL_DIR and the two OCR_*_MODEL_NAME values match what
#      was actually provisioned.
#   4. Recreate the containers if you changed INSTALL_OCR or model settings.
